h3. Issue Summary

When the Multimedia Macro is being used, it disables the Inline Comments in the page.
h3. Environment
 * Cloud
h3. Steps to Reproduce

 # Attach a video file to a page and use the Multimedia Macro to use the video in the page body;
 # Publish the page;
 # Try to add am Inline comment.

h3. Expected Results

The Inline comment (and "Create Issue" as well) option should appear.
h3. Actual Results

The Inline comment (and "Create Issue" as well) option doesn't appear.

 
h3. Workaround

I found two workarounds we can use:

*Use the video without the Multimedia Macro*:
# Delete the Multimedia Macro in the page;
# Go to the insert files option in the editor;
# Select the "Attached to this page" option and insert the video as a file;
# Publish the page;
# Inline comments are now able to be added.

*Delete the Multimedia Macro and then restore the previous version*:
# Edit the page and delete the Multimedia Macro;
# Publish the page;
# Go to the ellipses (at the top-right on the window) and select "Page History";
# Restore the page for the previous version;
# Now the Inline comments are available to be added.

h3. Summary

Error 500 is thrown when trying to insert a 'Page Index' macro into a page using the new editor;
h3. Environment
 * Error 500 when trying to insert 'Page Index' macro into a page that's using the new editor;
 * This behavior is not present when trying to insert this macro into a page using the old editor;
 * Behavior present in Firefox and Chrome;

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a page using the new editor;
 # Insert the 'Page Index' macro either by typing "/page index" OR by clicking '+' drop-down menu > "View More" > type 'Page Index';



h3. Expected Results
 * 'Page Index' macro to be inserted into the page;

h3. Actual Results
 * If macro is inserted via '+' drop-down menu: The load wheel keep spinning, No macro is inserted and Error 500 is thrown on browser's console - "message: "java.lang.NullPointerException: null""
 * If macro is inserted via typing "/page index": error 500 is thrown on browser's console and no macro is inserted;
 !Screen Shot 2019-03-18 at 17.24.55.png|thumbnail! 
 
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Summary

When using the  "K" key shortcut, to get a 'Link to this page' pop-up,  Confluence redirects users to Page properties instead.
This also happens if 'Link to this page' button is used instead of the keyboard shortcut (*...* > 'Link to this page');
 !Screen Shot 2019-03-14 at 17.06.26.png|thumbnail! 
This  behavior is present in pages that contain a *"Multimedia" macro*;
It seems intermittent as well, the only way that I was able to consistently reproduce this behavior was - accessing the page for the first via URL

h3. Environment
* Page containin "Multimidia" macro;


h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Navigate to a page containing "Multimidia"macro (preferably by accessing the page URL directly);
 # Hit the "k" key on the keyboard

h3. Expected Results
 * 'Link to this Page' pop-up should be displayed;.

h3. Actual Results
* User is redirected to the current page 'Page properties';

h3. Notes
If you navigate to an unaffected page, hit 'k' you'll get the 'Link to this Page' as expected. If you navigate back to the affected page, using the page tree for example, and hit 'k' the 'Link to this Page' pop up will be displayed correctly.

h3. Workaround
In this case there would be two possible workarounds:
* Remove the "Multimidia" macro from the page;
OR
* Navigate to an unaffected page (that do not contain this macro) and hit 'K'- the 'Link to this Page' pop-up will be displayed;
* Navigate back to the affected page, using the page tree, and hit 'K' on the affected page. This time 'Link to this Page' pop-up will be correctly displayed;

h3. Summary

When managing apps, if the admin clicks "+ Build a new app", Confluence throws a "Page Not Found"
h3. Environment

Confluence Cloud
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Log in as a Confluence admin;
 # Access the "Manage Apps" section;
 # Click + Build a new app;

h3. Expected Results

Confluence opens the correct page for these functions.
h3. Actual Results

Confluence throws a "Page Not Found" error instead.
h3. Workaround
Customers can visit the page linked from "build a new app" directly by pasting this URL in the browser:
 {noformat}
<site-name>/plugins/servlet/upm/develop?source=manage{noformat}
